Really awesome and useful gallery app when it works. If only it worked consistently. In fact you can tell it's the gold standard because about 80% of the other gallery apps that come up first in search on the Play store are stolen clones of earlier versions of this app, which you can tell down to the selection of settings in the settings menu and other menus. They clone it for a reason, on the surface this app has all the features you'd want including viewing GIFs and videos inline with regular images, pinning folders to the top, nesting folder views inside subfolders, launching the built in editor or your own editor, a basic slideshow function, copy/move/rename functions, even some things that I would rarely touch on Android like a Print button. You can even sort a folder by "random" which is great for when you just want to scroll through your collection and get a nice surprise. It's chock full o'stuff, to the point that some of it isn't even evident what it does. For example, there's a "favorite" function that lets you "favorite" an item and then... well nothing happens. Seriously, even the app's webpage that has all sorts of useful FAQs doesn't explain it. But that's a minor quibble. The real reason I had to take a star off was that the actual image detection and file manipulation is flaky. Now in most cases, these Gallery apps are faulty at finding files because they load from the Mediastore function in Android, which is notoriously flaky. But I'm familiar with this mess and have found apps to make sure that folders are updated in Mediastore, used other gallery apps to make sure they're in the Mediastore, and still they wouldn't appear in Simple Gallery. Then I manually added them using the Manage included folders feature and pulled to refresh, and it still wouldn't appear. Finally I gave up and shut the device off, pulled out the SD card, turned the device back on with the card out and magically the folders (which were on internal storage) appeared. I'm assuming that it prioritizes loading the SD first and times out or something but it's just weird behavior. There's all sorts of other weird inconsistent behavior when using the refresh inside the app or problems due to doing file operations outside the app, even when Mediastore clearly isn't the culprit. Also one other minor quibble, when you go to "move to" or "copy to" you get a very plain file manager view that always snaps back to the root, making it difficult to repeatedly move files if you don't have them all ready in one selection. This could be solved pretty easily with an option to 'sticky' the file manager selection though so I can't be too mad. Simple way around it is make your "target" folder temporarily a name that comes first in the file manager so that it will always show up first, then use some other file manager to move things around later. Still, out of the fifty or more gallery apps I tried this week (yes, really) this one is in my top three. The other two have major problems. Quickpic has been stolen and cloned almost as much as this app and the clones work worse, but the old version is still the best when it comes to reading files off a device. My other choice is the first result for 3D Gallery app, but it's cursed by relying on Mediastore, and has the weakest support for actually viewing images (won't go over a certain resolution). So this four-star app is still my #1 choice for now, especially if you don't count old apps that no longer update. Now, if I could just find a better dedicated slideshow app for my Android picture frame... || Edit: gotta take off another star. I found out where the favorites go (they just mysteriously showed up in a pinned 'folder' way way long after I favorited them and had moved on because I couldn't see where they went), but I tried moving some files instead of copying and the app completely derped out. I have two notifications sitting on my bar this morning that claim they are 'moving' two photos that I asked for since last night. Come on now, this isn't that hard to get right.

I 99% loved the free version, which I actually chose to pay for, anyway, but I did find that the support and vision was very lacking. Hopefully, now that it has gone "pro", both of these issues will be gone and motivate the developer to implement the one missing feature: make the recycle bin hideable along with other hidden folders. After all, people delete media from hidden locations and these should then not appear visible in the recycle bin as that breaches the whole intent of hidden folders and the optional password protection. As such, users should be able to designate the recycle bin as hidden allowing its content the same protection as normal hidden folders. Fix this, or make it an option, and this app will be complete.
